.TH UTILITYKIT 1 "July 2026" "UtilityKit v5.10.6" "UtilityKit Tools"
.SH NAME
utility-port_inspector \- Find which process is listening on a local TCP port, display network interface information, and optionally terminate the owning process.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B utility port_inspector
[\fIoptions\fP]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Find which process is listening on a local TCP port, display network interface information, and optionally terminate the owning process.
.SH FEATURES
.PP
.IP \(bu 4
\fBPort lookup\fP — identifies the process holding any local TCP port using \fClsof\fP or \fCss\fP
.IP \(bu 4
\fBInterface summary\fP — shows active network interfaces and their IP addresses
.IP \(bu 4
\fBProcess termination\fP — optionally sends \fCSIGTERM\fP to the process owning the port
.IP \(bu 4
\fBInteractive mode\fP — running without arguments launches a guided prompt
.IP \(bu 4
\fBCross-platform\fP — works on Linux, macOS, and Termux using available system tools
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH USAGE
.PP
.EX
bash _port_inspector/_port_inspector.sh 3000

bash _port_inspector/_port_inspector.sh 3000 --kill

bash _port_inspector/_port_inspector.sh
.EE
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH OPTIONS
.PP
Option   |   Description
\fCPORT\fP   |   The local TCP port number to inspect
\fC--kill\fP   |   Terminate the process owning the port without interactive confirmation
\fC-h, --help\fP   |   Show usage
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH HOW IT WORKS
.PP
The tool attempts port inspection in this order:
.PP
.IP \(em 4
Uses \fClsof -nP -iTCP:<port> -sTCP:LISTEN\fP if available
.IP \(em 4
Falls back to \fCss -ltnp sport = :<port>\fP if \fClsof\fP is not installed
.IP \(em 4
Extracts the PID from whichever tool succeeded
.IP \(em 4
Prompts whether to send \fCSIGTERM\fP to that PID (or skips the prompt with \fC--kill\fP)
.PP
Network interface output uses \fCip -brief addr\fP if available, falling back to \fCifconfig\fP.
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
.EX
bash _port_inspector/_port_inspector.sh 8080

bash _port_inspector/_port_inspector.sh 5432 --kill

.EE
.PP
.PP
.PP
.SH EXIT CODES
.PP
Code   |   Meaning
\fC0\fP   |   Success or no process found on that port
\fC1\fP   |   Missing required tools (\fClsof\fP and \fCss\fP both unavailable)
